        <fr:title text="What is a quiver?">What is a quiver?</fr:title>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
          <fr:month>6</fr:month>
          <fr:day>19</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link type="local" href="rui.xml" addr="rui" title="Rui Peixoto">Rui Peixoto</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p><fr:em>A quiver is just a directed graph with an attitude!</fr:em> While fully descriptive, this popular statement is hardly elucidating. It follows a beloved mathematical tradition  of explaining concepts in the most obtuse way possible.</fr:p>
        <fr:p>My goal today is to do exactly the opposite: I will introduce the simple concept of a quiver in obnoxious detail, from three different perspectives. Buckle up, and join me in discovering in how many ways we can understand a bunch of dots and arrows.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:anchor>247</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">quivers-0003</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>quivers-0003.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Quiver as a graph">Quiver as a graph</fr:title>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
          <fr:month>6</fr:month>
          <fr:day>19</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link type="local" href="rui.xml" addr="rui" title="Rui Peixoto">Rui Peixoto</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p>We start by the most pedestrian of approaches.</fr:p>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>241</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">quivers-0004</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>quivers-0004.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Quivers I">Quivers I</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>19</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link type="local" href="rui.xml" addr="rui" title="Rui Peixoto">Rui Peixoto</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A quiver consists of:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> of <fr:em>vertices</fr:em>;</fr:li>
	<fr:li>a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> of <fr:em>edges</fr:em>;</fr:li>
	<fr:li>a pair of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s, t \colon  E \rightarrow  V]]></fr:tex> named <fr:em>source</fr:em> and <fr:em>target</fr:em> maps.</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:p>Two sets, and two functions, that's it! Moreover, these carry very intuitive meanings. Consider the following example of a quiver.</fr:p>
        <fr:figure>
          <fr:resource hash="2e8d29a861d18feb7f21b0c9c0c0b65e">
            <fr:resource-content>
              <fr:img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," />
            </fr:resource-content>
            <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
		\usepackage {tikz}
		\usepackage {tikz-cd}
	]]></fr:resource-source>
            <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
		\begin {tikzcd}
		a \arrow [r, "v"] & b
		\end {tikzcd}
	]]></fr:resource-source>
          </fr:resource>
        </fr:figure>
        <fr:p>This consists of vertices <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V = \{a, b\}]]></fr:tex> and a single edge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E = \{v\}]]></fr:tex>.
The source and target maps encode the information that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> has a source <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(v) = a]]></fr:tex> and target <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(v) = b]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
